  </div>
</header>


<section class="hero">

  <Image class="hero" src={art1} alt="Logo art" aria-hidden="true" fetchpriority="high" />
  <h1>x86-64 Playground</h1>
  <h2>An online assembly editor and GDB-like debugger</h2>

  <div class="btgroup">
    <a class="action" href="/">Launch the app</a>
    <a href="#introduction">Learn more</a>
  </div>


</section>

<section id="introduction">
      <p>x86-64 Playground is a web app for experimenting and learning 
        x86-64 assembly.
      </p>
        <ul>
        <li>
        The Playground web app provides an online code editor where you
        can write, compile, and share assembly code for a wide
        range of popular assemblers such as GNU As, Fasm and Nasm.
        </li>
        <li>
        Unlike traditional onlide editors, this playground
          allows you to follow the execution of your program step by step,
        inspecting memory and registers of the running process from a GDB-like interface.
        </li>
        <li>
          You can bring your own programs!
        Drag and drop into the app any x86-64-Linux static executable to run and 
        debug it in the same sandboxed environment, without having to install anything.
        </li>
          </ul>

  <picture>
    <source srcset={screen1_webp.src} type="image/webp" >
    <img class="screen" src={screen1.src} alt="TODO" width={screen1.width} height={screen1.height} loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
  </picture>
</section>

<section>
  <h3>Who is this for</h3>
  <p>The app is for anyone that wants to run amd64 assembly snippets or
      inspect the inner workings of simple Linux ELF files.</p>
  <p>It has been designed with the academic world of binary exploitation in mind;
        The debugger interface offers visualizations similar to the GDB+PwnGDB debugger plugin,
        and all the controls are labelled with the respective GDB commands.
        </p>
        <p>In conjuction with Compiler Explorer, this app offers a good starting point to
      experiment with the core concepts behind the art of binary exploitation. It includes
        the guides and resources necessary to continue the experiments locally,
        on a Linux environment with GDB.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h3>An experience designed for the web </h3>

      <p>Have you ever seen a responsive debugger?
        The app has been designed with the mobile experience as
        a first class citizen, and can be embedded in any web page
        to add interactivity to technical tutorials or documentations.
      </p>
      <p>
        Follow the guide to <a href="#"> embed in your website </a> both the asm editor and debugger.
        <br/>
        <br/>
        </p>
  <picture>
    <source srcset={screen2_webp.src} type="image/webp" >
    <img class="screen" src={screen2.src} alt="TODO" width="300px" height="540px" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
  </picture>
</section>

<section>
  <h3>Offline-first and open-source</h3>

  <p>
  The app is open-source, and <a href="https://github.com/robalb/x86-64-playground">available on Github</a>.
  It's powered by the <a href="https://github.com/jart/blink/">Blink Emulator</a>,
  which emulates an x86-64-Linux environment entirely client side in your browser.
  This means that all the code you write, or the excutables you debug are never sent to the server.
  </p>
  <p>
  everything runs in your browser, and once the Web App loads it will work 
  without an internet connection.
  </p>
</section>

<style>
  section{
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    flex-direction: column;
    width: 100%;
    padding: 1rem;
    max-width: 850px;
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
  img.hero{
    max-width: 20rem;
    height: auto;
  }
  h1{
    color: var(--theme-primary);
    font-size: 3.5rem;
    line-height: 3rem;
    text-align: center;
    margin: .1rem;
    margin-top: 0;
    font-family: 'Neuton';
  }
  h2{
    color: var(--color-gray-100);
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 1.8rem;
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-family: 'Inter';
    font-weight:400;
  }
  h3{
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    line-height: 3rem;
    font-family: 'Neuton';
  }
  p,ul,li{
    width: 100%;
    line-height: 1.9rem;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-family: 'Inter';
    margin: .4rem;
  }
  p a{
    color: var(--color-gray-100);
    text-decoration-color: var(--theme-primary);
    text-decoration-thickness: 3px;
  }
  p a:hover{
    color: var(--color-gray-0);
  }

  @media screen and (min-width: 600px){
    h1{
      font-size: 3.5rem;
      line-height: 3.5rem;
    }
    h2{
      line-height: 1.8rem;
      font-size: 1.3rem;
    }
  }

  .btgroup {
    padding-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 5rem;
  }
  .btgroup a{
    font-size: 1.0rem;
    font-family: 'Inter';
    font-weight:600;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: var(--color-gray-100);
    padding: .5rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  .btgroup a:hover{
    color: var(--color-gray-0);
    background-color: var(--color-gray-300);
  }
  .btgroup a.action{
    --blue-gradient: linear-gradient(to right, #29ffc6, #20e3b2, #0cebeb);
    --orange-gradient: linear-gradient(to right, #ff5e62, #ff9966);
    color: var(--color-gray-500);
    background: var(--blue-gradient);
    margin-right: 1rem;
  }
  .btgroup a.action:hover{
    border-color: #fefefe;
  }

  img.screen{
    border: 2px solid black;
    display: block;
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    margin: 0 auto;
    object-fit: contain;
  }

</style>
<script>
    window.goatcounter = {
